If you run this code as it is, you will see that it does not output "Hello, Alice (after 1 second)" until after it has also outputted "Hello, Bob". This is because the `delay` function uses `setTimeout`, which executes asynchronously.
To fix this, we can change the `delay` function so that it returns a Promise instead of directly resolving after the specified delay:
```javascript
function delay(ms) {
    return new Promise(resolve => setTimeout(resolve, ms));
}
```
Now we can await the promise returned by `delay` in our `sayHello` function:
```javascript
async function sayHello(name) {
    const response = await delay(1000);
    console.log('Hello, ' + name);
}
```
This will output "Hello, Alice (after 1 second)" first, followed by "Hello, Bob" at the natural resolution of the browser's event loop.
